3.  Public Sector Procurement Specialist (24 person-months) 

6.  The expert will be responsible for providing inputs on Indonesian procurement practices 
and should have experience, preferably with a government agency, in project management and 
procurement methods. He or she should have expertise in current procurement regulations and 
be familiar with the procedures of ADB and other international financing institutions. The expert 
should hold a university degree in a related discipline such as business, law, or engineering, 
with more than 5 years’ experience in public procurement. The expert’s tasks will include  

(i)  leading the development of a procurement strategy and its implementation; 
(ii)  participating  in  country  procurement  assessments  and  preparing  background 
analysis; 
(iii)  assisting the NPPA to further develop and strengthen the public procurement 
system; 
(iv)  assisting  the  NPPA  to  draft  relevant  government  regulations  (peraturan 
pemerintah) to support the enactment of the Procurement Law; 
(v)  advising the team on the technical, commercial, and legal aspects of procurement 
at all stages, if an initial draft of the Procurement Law has been prepared; 
(vi)  improving  the  legal  and  operational  environment  by  providing  assistance  to 
ensure  full  harmonization  with  procurement  best  practice,  as  well  as  wider 
awareness and knowledge among procuring entities, potential suppliers, and the 
public; 
(vii)  upgrading public procurement rules by developing the administrative capacity 
and  efficiency  of  those  public  institutions  dealing  with  procurement,  in 
coordination with institutional development experts; 
(viii)  preparing monthly and quarterly progress reports for submission to ADB and the 
NPPA in a timely manner; and 
(ix)  coordinating  with  other  consultants  and  government  officials  to  prepare  TA 
inception and completion reports.
